    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>The Museo Nacional de Cerámica y Artes Suntuarias González Martí is Spain's national ceramics museum, located at Calle Poeta Querol, 2 in the historic centre of Valencia. The museum occupies the Palacio del Marqués de Dos Aguas, an 18th-century aristocratic palace declared a Historic-Artistic Monument. The palace's alabaster façade, completed in 1740–1744 by sculptor Ignacio Vergara, is one of the most elaborate examples of the Churrigueresque style in Spain. The collection was founded by ceramics scholar Manuel González Martí, who donated his holdings to the Spanish state in 1947.</p>
    <p>The museum holds the largest national ceramics collection in Spain, with pieces ranging from 8th-century Islamic ceramics through medieval Valencian tiles (azulejos), Renaissance majolica, porcelain from the Royal Factory of Alcora, and 20th-century works. The palace's state rooms are preserved with original 18th and 19th-century furnishings, including Rococo, Neoclassical, and Chinoiserie decorative elements from successive renovations. A collection of 18th-century carriages is also on display. The museum holds a dedicated library and archive specialising in ceramics and decorative arts, open by appointment for research visits.</p>
    <p>The museum is administered by Spain's Ministerio de Cultura. General admission is €3.00, paid at the door — no advance booking is required or available. Entry is free on Saturday afternoons from 16:00, on Sunday and public holiday mornings until 14:00, and throughout the month of March. The official website is cultura.gob.es/mnceramica. Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</p>
